{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500395"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:12:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:12:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1637"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1637"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.22,0.21,0.27,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1637"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116324"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1637"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1637"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98320"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"873"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1418"},{"type":"tags","id":"1989"},{"type":"tags","id":"1994"},{"type":"tags","id":"5866"},{"type":"tags","id":"5937"},{"type":"tags","id":"9542"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49642"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116324"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 68-year-old man presents with a 12 hour history of expressive dysphasia. His partner is able to provide some collateral information. The patient is normally fit and well, although he has been complaining of recurrent headaches recently and intermittent limb weakness, which he attributed to getting older and adapting back to life in Australia after having returned several months ago from living in Thailand for the past 10 years. He has a medical history of prostate cancer and prostatectomy about 16 years ago. He takes no regular medication. He is a former smoker, drinks 1-2 glasses of alcohol socially, and has a history of using IV drugs once when he was about 18 years old.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 132/78 mmHg, pulse 84/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 16/min. Apart from his dysphasia, nothing else abnormal is found on physical examination. Contrast-enhanced CT shows a solitary intra-axial left frontal mass with a thick, irregular/nodular enhancing rim around a heterogeneous necrotic core, ill-defined infiltrative margins, and disproportionate vasogenic oedema with sulcal effacement; no additional lesions or calcifications are seen (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebral abscess","Metastasis","Tuberculoma","Glioblastoma","Neurocysticercosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a solitary intra-axial left frontal mass with a thick, irregular/nodular enhancing rim around a heterogeneous necrotic core, ill-defined infiltrative margins, and disproportionate vasogenic oedema with sulcal effacement. These imaging features are characteristic of glioblastoma, which typically presents with thick, irregular ring enhancement, central necrosis, and extensive surrounding oedema that is disproportionate to the size of the enhancing lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll the options provided could produce a lesion with that pattern. However, \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic disease\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response as it will often present with multiple lesions - and the patient may already have symptoms of the primary disease. While metastases can show ring enhancement, they typically have smoother, thinner walls and the oedema is usually more proportionate to the lesion size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebral abscess\u003C/strong\u003E usually indicates infection elsewhere - and the patient has no symptoms suggestive of infection such as fever, elevated white cell count, or signs of systemic illness. His temperature is normal at 37.2\u00b0C, and there is no history of recent infections, dental procedures, or immunosuppression that would predispose to abscess formation. While the patient has a remote history of IV drug use, this occurred approximately 50 years ago and is unlikely to be relevant to his current presentation. Current or recent IV drug use would increase the risk of cerebral abscess due to bacteremia, but a single episode in the distant past does not significantly impact the differential diagnosis in this case. Additionally, abscesses typically show smooth, thin-walled ring enhancement rather than the thick, irregular enhancement seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculoma\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eneurocysticercosis\u003C/strong\u003E are rare, although not impossible in this case due to his history of living in south-east Asia, where picking up \u003Cem\u003Etaenia solium or mycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E is very possible. \u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculoma\u003C/strong\u003E remains a second possibility on the differential and this should be stated on the referral for an MRI and to the neurosurgeons so appropriate MRI acquisitions can be taken and considered. If still a possibility when referred to the neurosurgeon appropriate biopsies would be sent to microbiology and PPE precautions during surgery. However, tuberculomas typically show more uniform enhancement and are often associated with other intracranial tuberculosis findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThus, the most likely disease is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eglioblastoma\u003C/strong\u003E. They are aggressive which could account for the variety of new symptoms and rapid progress in a short time frame, the median age of diagnosis is 64 years old, and it is more common in men than in women. The imaging findings of thick, irregular enhancement with central necrosis and disproportionate oedema are classic for glioblastoma. Of course, definitive diagnosis would require histological proof.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Differentials for ring-enhancing lesions on neuroimaging include: metastasis, abscess, glioblastoma, infection, contusion (which can be remembered with the mnemonic \u0022MAGIC\u0022)."],"references":["American Association of Neurological Surgeons. Glioblastoma Multiforme \u2013 Symptoms, Diagnosis and Treatment Options [Internet]. Aans.org. 2019. Available from: https://www.aans.org/en/Patients/Neurosurgical-Conditions-and-Treatments/Glioblastoma-Multiforme","Gaillard, F., Knipe, H. Cerebral ring enhancing lesions. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org. (accessed on 03 Apr 2022) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-6679"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98320"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1637"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15587"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15587"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eb08a80b-019d-4a09-97db-a1a69d88ba7d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eb08a80b-019d-4a09-97db-a1a69d88ba